title: Contemporary Vietnamese Architecture in the Information Age
description:
These are exciting times for architects and the public as architecture moves beyond modernism into the information age. This presentation focuses on the characteristics of this new architecture and shows how Vietnamese architects are leading the world in the design of houses and schools for the new reality of the information age.

About the speaker: American architect Mel Schenck is a long-term immigrant to Vietnam and has been studying Vietnamese modernist architecture since he was surprised by the extent and quality of this architecture in Saigon when he first lived here in 1971/72. He and photographer Alexandre Garel are the authors of the new book "Southern Vietnamese Modernist Architecture: Mid-Century Vernacular Modernism" published in Hanoi by Th·∫ø Gi·ªõi Publishers.

title: Southern Vietnam as a Center of Modernist Architecture
description:
The vast quantity and quality of Vietnamese modernist buildings constructed throughout southern Vietnam between 1945 and 1975 made Vietnam an unrecognized center of modernism in the world. ***About the speaker: American architect Mel Schenck is a long-term immigrant to Vietnam and has been studying Vietnamese modernist architecture since he was surprised by the extent and quality of this architecture in Saigon when he first lived here in 1971/72. The Foreign Ministers of Mekong countries, including Cambodia, Lao PDR, Myanmar, Thailand, and Vietnam and the Secretary of State of the United States of America, on September 11, 2020, launched the #MekongUSPartnership, building on the success of the Lower Mekong Initiative. The Foreign Ministers and the Secretary reaffirmed the strong friendship and successful collaboration between the United States and countries in the Mekong region. They also affirmed that the Mekong-U.S. Partnership will further strengthen transparency and good governance, and enhance connectivity, economic integration, inclusive, and sustainable development, and help narrow the development gap in the region.  The new Partnership will broaden and deepen our cooperation and allow for flexibility in addressing emerging issues. Read the entire statement here: https://www.state.gov/mekong-u-s-partnership-joint-ministerial-statement/

title: Using Satellite Technology to Learn About our World
description:
Can space help us understand earth? The NASA Land-Cover and Land-Use Change (LCLUC) satellite program uses images from space to help us observe changes on earth, including important data about natural disasters, the environmental changes, the effects of agriculture, and the health of forests and wetlands. Scientists use this data to inform decisionmakers about the possible effects of natural and manmade changes. 

Join us for a presentation by Dr. Garik Gutman, the LCLUC Program Manager at NASA Headquarters, on the program‚Äôs achievements and   NASA‚Äôs science collaboration with the Vietnam National Space Center (VNSC), followed by  a panel discussion about the challenges Vietnam is currently facing and how the United States and Vietnam are working together to learn more.

*By attending our events, you agree to be photographed and/or filmed and give permission to use your likeness in promotional and/or marketing materials. Children under 15 years of age are not allowed in the American Center. Passport/CMND is required for entry.

title: Moving Back and Looking Ahead
description:
Panelists:
‚Ä¢ Bao Nguyen - Filmmaker
‚Ä¢ Chi Ha ‚Äì American Education Group Vietnam
‚Ä¢ Alexander Tu Nguyen ‚Äì SOUL Music & Performing Arts 
‚Ä¢ Ken Dat Duong ‚Äì TDL Law Firm
‚Ä¢ Lien Hoang ‚Äì Bloomberg BNA

The final panel in our series of Vietnamese-Americans living in HCMC will discuss the paths that led them to moving to Vietnam and their experiences living here. The panelists will also share their predictions for where they see HCMC going in the future, how they think the city will continue to develop, and what role the diaspora community will play in that growth.

title: Then- Now: Navigating the Generation Gap in Vietnamese Culture
description:
Panelists: 
Jenni Trang Le ‚Äì Filmmaker
Khanh Nguyen ‚Äì U.S. Consulate
Melinh Rozen ‚Äì Everest Education
Khanh Nguyen ‚Äì Attorney 

Across the globe, each generation often struggles to connect with the next. What does that look like for Vietnamese families? The panel of Vietnamese-Americans living in HCMC will discuss cross-generational communication within both the Vietnamese and American cultural context.

title: Vietnamese and Vi·ªát Ki·ªÅu: Same, Same or Different?
description:
Panelists:
Mimi Vu, Director of Advocacy & Strategic Partnerships, Pacific Links
Don Le, Co-founder, Everest Education
Don Phan, Entrepreneur
Anh-Thu Nguyen, Baker & McKenzie
What are the cultural similarities and differences between Vietnamese-Americans and Vietnamese? Are all Vietnamese connected regardless of where they grew up? Hear from some Vietnamese-Americans who are living in HCMC about what has surprised them, fitting in versus standing out, and what gives them a sense of belonging.
